{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01MKucfgZ51pm7DhqmUPUyVN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Same - only GC logs. ES (both 7.x and 8.x) in containerized mode writes regular cluster logs to stdout, not to files. Only GC logs go to the filesystem.\n\nThis means Filebeat with `*.log` pattern will pick up `gc.log` but not the ES cluster logs. Let me update the Filebeat config to:\n1. Also match `gc.log` for capture (or)\n2. Change approach to capture logs from ES stdout\n\nSince we can't read from the container's stdout in a sidecar without host paths or privilege, the best approach for Filebeat is to read the GC logs (which ARE in the shared emptyDir) and also configure Filebeat to read from the Kubernetes API for pod logs.\nActually, I'm realizing the fundamental issue here - in containerized mode, ES logs to stdout which the container runtime captures to host node paths that a sidecar can't access without HostPath volumes. The typical Filebeat sidecar pattern assumes ES writes to files, but since the task requires both Metricbeat and Filebeat as sidecars, I need to find a way to make Filebeat work within those constraints. Let me think through the viable options. the default log4j2 configuration in the containerized ES setup writes to stdout rather than to files, even though `path.logs` points to a directory. I should check if there's a cluster configuration file that might give me more insight into what's actually being logged.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":314,"cache_read_input_tokens":71416,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":314},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e46c215e-a358-4899-91cd-9184d094f1e6","uuid":"3de8481